title.narrative: DEMAND OF SERVICES AND CONTINUUM OF CARE

description.narrative: By 2020, children, adolescents and their families have the knowledge and ability required to seek HIV prevention, care and treatment services and remain in the continuum of care in UNICEF-supported districts, which contributes to Hiv Prevention, Treatment And Care Of Children Living With Hiv. UNICEF aims to achieve this through Advocacy And Public Engagement, Fostering Innovation And Use Of New Technologies, Systems Strengthening And Institution Building, United Nations Working Together. This contributes to the following Country Programme result: School-age children, particularly girls and those in vulnerable regions, have access to quality basic education, including in emergency situations.

title.narrative: By 2020, children, adolescents and their families have the knowledge and ability required to seek HIV prevention, care and treatment services and remain in the continuum of care in UNICEF-supported districts

description.narrative: Since the beginning of the year, more than 291 670 people are registered on the U-Report platform. In the 10 priority health districts, the 12-months retention rates for HIV positive patients on ART were 72.6% for children and adolescents and 66.3% for pregnant and breastfeeding women at the end of 2018. Comprehensive knowledge about HIV, although still poor, has generally increased. Among the 15-19 age group, 37.2% among girls and 32.9% among boys clearly identify means to prevent transmission of HIV. | Status:On-track | As-of Date:30/06/2020
